<DOC><DOCNO> AP900109-0071 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-90 0751EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-India-Kashmir     01-09 0361</FIRST><SECOND>PM-India-Kashmir,0371</SECOND><HEAD>Moslem Separatists Kill Officer; Police Fatally Shoot TwoDemonstrators</HEAD><BYLINE>By ARUN JOSHI</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>JAMMU, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Officials in the northern state ofJammu-Kashmir said Moslem separatists fatally shot a police officertoday, and witnesses said police opened fire to disperse Moslemdemonstrators in Srinagar, killing two people.   The separatists also set fire to government buildings to protestalleged police brutality, officials said.   Authorities clamped an indefinite curfew on Srinagar and threeother towns and called out the army to prevent further violence, astate government spokesman said.   The spokesman, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,said 15 people were killed today and Monday but he did not give anybreakdown of the deaths.   On Monday, at least 14 people were killed and more than 100injured when police opened fire on demonstrators in Srinagar andthe neighboring town of Sopore, witnesses said. At least one of theinjured people died of their wounds today, they said.   Chief Secretary Moosa Raza, the state's top civil servant, saidan inspector from the intelligence wing of the police was shot andkilled by Moslem militants in Bureava, 19 miles west of Srinagar.   In Bandipur, 28 miles north of Srinagar, demonstrators set twogovernment buildings ablaze, he said.   Scores of people have been killed in the state in recent weeksas police cracked down on Moslems seeking independence for theKashmir region of the state or union with neighboring Pakistan.   Jammu-Kashmir state is the only state with a Moslem majority inIndia, where 82 percent of the national population of 880 millionis Hindu.   India and predominantly Moslem Pakistan have fought three warsover Kashmir since both gained independence in 1947. Part ofKashmir is under Pakistan's control. A cease-fire line monitored bythe United Nations divides the region into Indian and Pakistanisectors.   Moslems comprise 64 percent of Jammu-Kashmir's 5 million people.The Kashmir part of the state is mostly Moslem, while the Jammusection is mostly Hindu. Nationwide, Moslems account for about 12percent of India's population.   Srinagar is the summer capital of the state and Jammu, 95 milesto the south, is the winter capital.</TEXT></DOC>